<div class="body">

<h2>What is MSG / DSG?</h2>
<p>Monosodium glutamate (MSG) is the sodium salt of glutamic acid, an amino acid. Unlike naturally occurring glutamate in proteins, MSG is <em>manufactured free glutamic acid</em> that does not occur naturally in food.</p>
<p>Disodium glutamate (DSG) is similar but contains two sodium ions instead of one. Both MSG and DSG break down into glutamate (glutamic acid) in the body.</p>
<p>Chemical formula: C<sub>5</sub>H<sub>8</sub>NO<sub>4</sub>Na (MSG)</p>

<h2>Health Concerns</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Excitotoxicity</strong> (glutamate storms) - overstimulation of neurons</li>
<li>Linked to: migraines, diabetes, multiple sclerosis, rheumatoid arthritis</li>
<li>May suppress immune system</li>
<li>Effects are <strong>cumulative</strong> with repeated exposure</li>
</ul>

<h2>The Problem</h2>
<ul>
<li>MSG is widely used in processed foods and quick-service restaurants (QSRs)</li>
<li>Restaurants are <strong>not required</strong> to disclose MSG use (trade secret)</li>
<li>Labeling laws don't require quantity disclosure</li>
<li>"No MSG" is impossible &mdash; only "no added MSG" is accurate</li>
</ul>

<h2>Key Facts</h2>
<ul>
<li>FDA considers up to <strong>30mg</strong> of MSG without food as "safe"</li>
<li>25% of population reacts to high doses of MSG</li>
<li>Average intake: 0.3-1.7g/day depending on diet</li>
<li>Hidden names include: yeast extract, hydrolyzed protein, autolyzed plant protein, disodium guanylate</li>
</ul>

<h2>Mission</h2>
<p>To study the effects of consuming monosodium glutamate (MSG), especially over the long term, and to advocate for better labeling and disclosure in restaurants and processed foods.</p>
